{{page-title "Documentation — Cover Letters"}}
<div class="container mx-auto max-w-3xl py-6 px-4 space-y-6">

  <Panel::Card>
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">Cover Letters</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      Cover letters in Career Caddy are AI-generated drafts tailored to a specific job post.
      The AI reads the job description and your Career Data, then writes a letter in your
      voice — not a generic template. You can edit the result before using it.
    </p>
    {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of a generated cover letter" /> --}}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">How Generation Works</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-3">
      From any Job Post detail page, click "Generate Cover Letter." The AI receives:
    </p>
    <ul class="text-gray-600 text-sm list-disc list-inside space-y-1 mb-3">
      <li>The full job description</li>
      <li>Your Career Data (background, skills, voice)</li>
      <li>Any favorited cover letters or answers you've previously produced</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      The result is a first draft in your voice. Review it, edit as needed, then use it
      when applying. The better your Career Data, the less editing you'll need to do.
    </p>
    {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of cover letter generation form" /> --}}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">The Favorite Feedback Loop</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      When you mark a cover letter as a <strong>favorite</strong>, it becomes part of the
      AI's context for future generations. The AI learns from your best output — the letters
      you keep are writing samples that teach it your voice. Over time, generations require
      less editing.
    </p>
    {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot showing the favorite star on a cover letter" /> --}}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Example Cover Letter</h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-50 border border-gray-200 rounded p-4 text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-3">
      <p>
        I've spent eight years building backend systems that handle real traffic, and I've
        learned that the gap between a system that works in staging and one that works in
        production is almost always about edge cases no one thought to test. That's the
        kind of thinking I bring to every project.
      </p>
      <p>
        At Meridian Health, I rebuilt the patient intake API from scratch after it became
        a bottleneck — response times went from 1.2 seconds to 180ms by shifting to async
        workers. It wasn't glamorous work, but it was the right call, and I made the case
        for it without needing approval theater. I suspect Acme Corp values that same
        judgment: your job description mentions owning features end-to-end, which is exactly
        the kind of scope where I do my best work.
      </p>
      <p>
        I'd love to talk. I'm particularly interested in the platform team's roadmap —
        if you're at the stage of making architectural decisions that will shape how the
        product scales, that's when a conversation is most valuable.
      </p>
    </div>
    {{!-- <img src="" alt="screenshot of a cover letter in the show view with edit and favorite controls" /> --}}
  </Panel::Card>

</div>
